LABS
White count 12.1; hemoglobin 9.9; platelets 255; total bilirubin 0.4; direct 0.2; alk-phos 37; AST 277; creatinine 0.5.  Preoperative imaging studies reviewed.
IMPRESSION/REPORT/PLAN
#1 Colon adenocarcinoma with evidence of nodal and hepatic metastatic disease
Mrs. Register has colon cancer with nodal involvement as well as multiple areas of hepatic involvement.  She has undergone what sounds like a gross total resection at this time, although the surgical note is not yet posted.
I discussed the nature of stage IV colon cancer with Mrs. Register and her husband today.  We discussed the fact that even in the setting of a gross total resection, there are likely areas of micrometastatic disease at this point and thus her risk of recurrence is very high.  Given this, we would recommend that she undergo postoperative chemotherapy and we would recommend 12 cycles of FOLFOX in this setting.  Given the fact that this postoperative treatment could truly be considered for metastatic disease as opposed to in the adjuvant setting, bevacizumab could be considered as well.
These recommendations were discussed in general terms with Mrs. Register and her husband.  Also discussed was the generally poor prognosis of patient's with stage IV colon cancer, as well as the fact that with resection of metastatic disease as well as postoperative chemotherapy, there can be an improvement in recurrence and long-term survival rates.
Given the fact that Mrs. Register's previous colonoscopy did not encompass the entire colon, we would also recommend that she undergo another colonoscopy within six-months in an effort to ensure there are no other lesions of concern.
#2 Low-grade endometrial stromal sarcoma
Mrs. Register has what appears to be a low-grade sarcoma which is confined to the uterus at this time without evidence of local invasion or nodal spread.  For this reason, I think observation is a reasonable course of action at this time.  Should she develop evidence of distant disease, progesterones would be reasonable, and we would recommend the avoidance of estrogen therapy in this setting.
Mrs. Register plans to receive her care at the BAMH Connecticut in Brandamore.  We will forward all our records to that center, and we will plan on her receiving her care there.  For that reason we will not be setting up any follow-up with medical oncology at this time, although we reenforced that should she have questions, concerns, or want a further opinion, we would be happy to see her back at any time in the Golden State Palms Convalescent of Ottumwa Center.
Thank-you very much for involving us in Mrs. Register's care.  Please feel free to contact us with questions or concerns via the Medical Oncology Consult pager (563-915-23693).
ADDENDUM:  Final path report confirms preliminary.  Colon cancer staged as pT3N2aM1a with 5/14 nodes positive.  Uterine specimen reveals low-grade endometrial stromal sarcoma forming a 5.2 x 3.7 x 3.0 cm polypoid mass in the endometrial cavity with focal invasion into the underlying myometrium.  The margins of resection are negative for malignancy. 47 sampled lymph nodes negative (jsb 9/10/10 1545)

