[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Register is a very pleasant 58-year-old female from Eau Claire who has had intermittent rectal bleeding for five years.  She states that this was typically blood-streaked stools, and for this she underwent a colonoscopy in June of 2005 which revealed two hyperplastic polyps which were removed.  Subsequently in follow-up she had another colonoscopy in February of 2009 which was per report unremarkable.
Mrs. Register reports that over the course of the past six-months this rectal bleeding got significantly worse to the point where in the late spring she was having five to six loose bowel movements a day with a significant blood content.  Also, over the last six-months she has lost approximately 40 pounds and been suffering from increasing nausea, mild abdominal pain and fatigue.
Given these symptoms, in May of 2010, upon returning from their winter stay in California, Mrs. Register presented to her primary-care provider, and an evaluation was undertaken.  A CT-scan was performed on June 8, 2010 which revealed a 2- x 2.3-cm lesion in the left lobe of the liver concerning for a metastatic deposit as well as an apparent enhancing mass in the endometrial canal with dilatation of the endometrial canal.  Per report, the initial read of this CT-scan did not reveal evidence of a sigmoid lesion, but our over read here at Milwaukee University of Iowa Family Care Center does suggest irregular thickening of the wall of the sigmoid colon.
Given these findings, Mrs. Register subsequently underwent a colonoscopy on July 13, 2010 which reveled a 25-cm circumferential sigmoid mass.  Biopsy of this region revealed invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma.  It should be noted that this colonoscopy only went to the transverse colon due to discomfort.  Further evaluation of these multiple abnormal findings in Florence included a pelvic ultrasound on July 27, 2010 revealing a 3.5-cm heterogenous solid lobulated mass throughout the central aspect of the uterus.  At this point, Mrs. Register transferred her care to RH in an effort to expedite the evaluation and potential treatment.
Mrs. Register presented to Milwaukee University of Iowa Family Care Center in early August of 2010 and was evaluated by Colorectal, Hepatic, and GYN Surgery.  As part of this evaluation, on August 3, 2010 an endometrial biopsy was performed which revealed a low-grade endometrial stromal neoplasm.  The result of this evaluation was a recommendation to proceed with a multidisciplinary surgical procedure including resection of the primary sigmoid lesion, any areas of obvious metastatic disease of the liver, as well as her uterus.
Mrs. Register underwent this combination surgery on September 2, 2010.  The operative note is not yet posted, but per the postprocedure note, an open sigmoidectomy, TAH/BSO, and resection of segments 3, 5, 6, and 8 of the liver, as well as bilateral pelvic and periaortic lymphadenopathy was performed.  The preliminary pathology reports from this procedure are consistent with an adenocarcinoma of the sigmoid colon with multiple areas of hepatic metastatic disease.  Five of 14 lymph nodes in the abdomen were positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma.  Per report, the uterine pathology is consistent with a low-grade endometrial stromal sarcoma, without evidence of extrauterine spread and negative pelvic lymph nodes.  The final path results are still pending at this time.
Mrs. Register is now postop day No. 1.  She is in significant pain, although her PCA does help with the pain control.  She has not passed flatus or stool as of yet and also has some nausea.  She frankly denies fevers, chills, chest pain, shortness-of-breath, focal neurologic symptom, or urinary symptoms at this time.

